post_text:
Due to the recent rush to enrollment at PA Cyber Charter School, enrollment demand has exceeded available seats. Families interested in future enrollment will be placed on a waiting list. As seats become available, admission to the school will be based on lottery system amongst all new, waiting list applicants. Siblings of active students will be given priority over new students. Those siblings will be exempted from the lottery as seats become available.
Primary caretakers of students selected through the lottery will be notified by both email and telephone with two (2) school days to accept or decline enrollment. That primary caretaker MUST complete the enrollment process by supplying compliance documents within ten (10) school days from the date the first notification was sent. Families of prospective students who are not compliant by the 10th day will forfeit their seat to the next eligible student on the waiting list.

PA Cyber is a TUITION FREE, K-12th grade public school, open for enrollment by any school-age child residing in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.
To learn more about PA Cyber from the comfort of your own home, please join us for one of our upcoming online information sessions. Dates and times can be found at http://www.pacyber.org/session

If you are ready to start the enrollment process for the 2020-2021 school year, please complete and submit the information request form at http://www.pacyber.org/enroll/ A PA Cyber representative will contact you within 2-3 business days. You may also call 1-888-722-9237 to speak to an Enrollment Representative.

PACYBER.ORG
Information Sessions
text:
PA Cyber is a TUITION FREE, K-12th grade public school, open for enrollment by any school-age child residing in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.
To learn more about PA Cyber from the comfort of your own home, please join us for one of our upcoming online information sessions. Dates and times can be found at http://www.pacyber.org/session

If you are ready to start the enrollment process for the 2020-2021 school year, please complete and submit the information request form at http://www.pacyber.org/enroll/ A PA Cyber representative will contact you within 2-3 business days. You may also call 1-888-722-9237 to speak to an Enrollment Representative.

PACYBER.ORG
Information Sessions

Today we salute 6th-grader Paden Costanzo for doing his part during the pandemic. Between mid-March and late May, Paden had delivered about 40 dozen eggs to his neighbors, which they especially appreciated as egg prices soared. Every day, Paden cares for about a dozen hens and one duck, including his favorite, ‚ÄúCluck Norris," ü§£ who provide the eggs.
Paden has also been helping neighbors with yard work and is happy to do it, because he feels it‚Äôs important we all take care of each other. His motto: "Small deeds can make a big difference to others and it‚Äôs easy enough to come up with something simple that you can do to help others."

Eggsellent job, Paden!ü•ö
#PACyberProud

A message from GSA President, Kim Sauers:
To our GSA club members, as well as all of those celebrating Pride right now, I would like to wish you a happy June and a happy summer! I know that celebration can be difficult at the moment, but there are plenty of online Pride parades and celebrations in which you can participate. In addition, I would like to thank GSA advisor, Mrs. Carrie Miller, for helping to create a safe and welcoming environment for all people. Being a member of the GSA club has been a wonderful and unforgettable experience, and I would like to thank all of you who helped to make the club what it is today.

This year the Science Club hosted the ‚ÄúGreat Backyard Bird Count.‚Äù Students from all over the state observed and recorded their sightings to a central site ‚Äì there were over 2000 bird sightings recorded and an amazing 49 species, from the very common song sparrow and robin to the rare cormorant, pileated woodpecker and bald eagle. We are so happy to encourage young ornithologists and hope that everyone continues to keep their eyes open to see more of the wonderful world we live in. Thanks to Mrs. Butler for this great video featuring our students' submissions.
http://ow.ly/yzKi50zyO0w

post_text:
Last Friday, based on the Governor‚Äôs order that all schools close for two weeks, PA Cyber complied. From that time and throughout the weekend, we sought additional information from the PA Department of Education and our cyber school colleagues to better understand what this means to an online school. Both Governor Wolf and Education Secretary Rivera suggested that cyber schools could provide continuity of education as long as they ensure social distancing.
Therefore, we will return to educational instruction, including live teaching and tutoring, across all of our modes of instruction on Wednesday, March 18, 2020.
Regional offices will remain closed and no FamilyLink activities, field trips, or other social/extracurricular activities will occur until further notice. We will reassess our plans for the remainder of the school year as new information comes available.
Please check your PA Cyber email for more details.

Hats off to the outstanding students in our DECA club, who competed at the Pennsylvania DECA conference in Hershey! With over 2,350 participants, 61 competitive events, and 21 student workshops, our students did an excellent job representing the best at PA Cyber!

Pennsylvania needs a better charter rule, plus school choice support from Governor Wolf | Opinion

PA Charter Schools
February 24 at 6:01 PM ¬∑

"Though Governor Tom Wolf often touts his willingness to bring stakeholders together to collaborate, it seems that invitation only applies to individuals who share his political ideologies. By making draconian cuts to charter school funding, Governor Wolf is proposing a public education system that discriminates against children based on what public school choices their families make, and that is something our Commonwealth cannot stand for." - Ana Meyers, PA Charter Schools Executive Director

post_text:
Our Engineering Exploration Experience (EEE) group began planning for their community project with the Emmaus Community of Pittsburgh. This spring, the group will be building a shed for our South Side neighbor and constructing window boxes once the shed is made.

Special thanks to Keith Barnhart, who works for the Emmaus House, for his input on tools and needs. Also to Dr. Deb Lange of Carnegie Mellon University for helping students build a miniature window box. She used a laser cutter for the wood and had all of the materials available for the students. They discussed how scaling projects down works in engineering terms.

#thelearningneverstops
